  {
    "url": "https://finance.yahoo.com/news/brace-yourself-nvidia-amd-gpu-173903954.html",
    "title": "Brace yourself: Nvidia and AMD GPU prices may rise as top AIBs adjust costs",
    "detail": "Brace yourself: Nvidia and AMD GPU prices may rise as top AIBs adjust costs\nShikhar Mehrotra\nSat, January 24, 2026 at 10:39 AM MST 2 min read\nIn this article:\nNVDA\nAMD\n2377.TW\nASUUY\n2376.TW\n\nThe memory crisis has already forced several PC and laptop manufacturers to adjust their retail pricing since the beginning of the year. However, a new report from China Times suggests that major Taiwanese graphics card manufacturers will increase prices for AMD and Nvidia RTX 50 series cards.\n\nAccording to the report, MSI has already announced the second round of price revisions for the Nvidia RTX 50 series, while Asus and Gigabyte could announce new pricing by the end of the month. Moreover, this could mark the \u201cbeginning of a price increase cycle for AMD and Nvidia graphics cards,\u201d reads the report translated from Chinese (Traditional).\n\nNvidia Unsplash\nExpect to see GPU prices rise quietly\n\nThe price increase for DDR6 and DDR7 VRAM modules (used in graphics cards) has compelled AMD and Nvidia to raise their supply or wholesale prices by 10-15% (depending on the model).\n\nNow, it is up to the partner manufacturer to decide whether they can absorb the higher cost or pass it along to customers through higher retail prices. Usually, retail partners like Asus, Gigabyte, and MSI don\u2019t officially announce new MSRPs via press releases.\n\nInstead, one has to spot price changes in retail listings, fewer base models, the abundance of premium SKUs (with higher price tags), or the silent delisting of older-priced inventory. The pattern becomes apparent once you start comparing the recent listing with those from a few weeks (or months) ago.\n\nNvidia Unsplash\n\nThe report notes that the prices of the AMD RX 9000 series GPUs have increased by 10-18% in markets such as Europe and China. Similarly, the price revision ranges from 15 to 20% for Nvidia RTX 50 series models with 16GB of higher VRAM.\n\nNvidia has an interesting strategy for the situation. The company is reportedly prioritizing RTX 50-series cards (which make the most commercial sense), namely the 8GB VRAM models like the RTX 5060 and 5060 Ti. Why? Because they\u2019re cheaper to make, easier to sell, and far less likely to attract a hefty price revision.\n\nThe higher-end variants, like the RTX 5080 and 5090, aren\u2019t disappearing from the market, but you might start seeing them less often on shelves. They might still be available, but at a higher price. For now, the GPU manufacturing partners have acknowledged the pressure but have yet to devise a suitable strategy (or set new price tags for the popular models).\n\nTerms and Privacy Policy\nPrivacy Dashboard",
    "date": null,
    "summaries": {
      "gemma4:e4b": "Price increases are anticipated for AMD graphics cards due to sector reports, suggesting a positive impact on revenue."
    },
    "sentiment_scores": {
      "gemma4:e4b": 0.9666
    }
  },
  {
    "url": "https://finance.yahoo.com/news/riot-platforms-riot-quietly-recasting-171124777.html",
    "title": "Is Riot Platforms (RIOT) Quietly Recasting Its Bitcoin Identity With This AMD AI Data Center Deal?",
    "detail": "Is Riot Platforms (RIOT) Quietly Recasting Its Bitcoin Identity With This AMD AI Data Center Deal?\nSimply Wall St\nSat, January 24, 2026 at 10:11 AM MST 3 min read\nIn this article:\nRIOT\nAMD\nBTC-USD\n\nEarlier in January 2026, Riot Platforms announced a 10-year, 25MW data center lease and services agreement with AMD at its Rockdale, Texas site, with options that could significantly expand AMD\u2019s access to AI and high-performance computing capacity.\n\nThis deal marks a meaningful broadening of Riot\u2019s business model as it seeks to pair its large power footprint with long-term AI infrastructure tenants, reducing reliance on Bitcoin mining alone.\n\nNext, we\u2019ll examine how this AMD agreement reshapes Riot Platforms\u2019 investment narrative, especially its push into AI-focused data center leasing.\n\nAI is about to change healthcare. These 109 stocks are working on everything from early diagnostics to drug discovery. The best part - they are all under $10b in market cap - there's still time to get in early.\n\nWhat Is Riot Platforms' Investment Narrative?\n\nTo own Riot today, you have to believe it can evolve from a pure-play Bitcoin miner into a credible power-and-data infrastructure platform, without losing financial discipline along the way. The AMD deal is a clear step in that direction: a 10-year, 25MW lease that begins to validate Riot\u2019s Rockdale build-out and introduces a second, contracted revenue stream tied to AI and high-performance computing. In the near term, key catalysts still centre on Bitcoin pricing, mining economics and how quickly additional data center capacity is pre-leased, but this agreement shifts some investor focus toward tenancy quality and utilization of Riot\u2019s 700MW interconnection. At the same time, it slightly reframes the risk set, adding execution and capital allocation questions on large-scale data center development to existing concerns around earnings volatility, dilution from the recent US$600.53 million equity raise and a rich earnings multiple.\n\nYet behind the AI story, heavy share issuance and earnings swings remain issues investors should not ignore.\n\nOur expertly prepared valuation report on Riot Platforms implies its share price may be too high.\n\nExploring Other Perspectives\nRIOT 1-Year Stock Price Chart\n\nFive fair value estimates from the Simply Wall St Community span roughly US$17.19 to US$38.12, showing how far apart individual expectations sit. Set those views against Riot\u2019s new AMD data center lease and the company\u2019s still-volatile earnings profile, and it becomes clear why you may want to weigh multiple perspectives before deciding how resilient this business model really is.\n\nExplore 5 other fair value estimates on Riot Platforms - why the stock might be worth over 2x more than the current price!\n\nBuild Your Own Riot Platforms Narrative\n\nDisagree with this assessment? Create your own narrative in under 3 minutes - extraordinary investment returns rarely come from following the herd.\n\nStory Continues\nTerms and Privacy Policy\nPrivacy Dashboard",
    "date": null,
    "summaries": {
      "gemma4:e4b": "AMD secured a 10-year, 25MW data center lease, positively boosting its AI capacity and infrastructure access."
    },
    "sentiment_scores": {
      "gemma4:e4b": 0.966
    }
  },
  {
    "url": "https://finance.yahoo.com/news/citi-analysts-love-1-lesser-160002706.html",
    "title": "Citi Analysts Love This 1 Lesser-Known Chip Stock Ahead of Earnings",
    "detail": "Citi Analysts Love This 1 Lesser-Known Chip Stock Ahead of Earnings\nChris MacDonald\nSat, January 24, 2026 at 9:00 AM MST 3 min read\nIn this article:\nNVDA\nAMD\n\nGrowth investors have plenty of world-class options to choose from. Whether it's groundbreaking technologies like autonomous vehicles, machine learning, blockchain, virtual reality, or artificial intelligence, one thing is for certain: the future is now.\n\nThe ability for investors to put some capital to work in the technologies of tomorrow is exciting, and in many respects, this period of time is like no other. Most investors (be they growth-oriented or not) understand the AI revolution is absolutely powering the U.S. economy right now. Powering this growth are high-performance computing chips provided by the likes of Nvidia (NVDA), Advanced Micro Devices (AMD), and others.\n\nMore News from Barchart\n\nIntel Stock Drops After Q4 Earnings: Is INTC a Buy Now?\n\nCould a Wearable AI Pin Be the Next Big Thing for Apple Stock?\n\nThe Most Expensive Question Investors Ask\n\nStop Missing Market Moves: Get the FREE Barchart Brief \u2013 your midday dose of stock movers, trending sectors, and actionable trade ideas, delivered right to your inbox. Sign Up Now!\n\nThat said, there are other overlooked chip stocks worth considering heading into earnings. Let's dive into what Citi analyst Atif Malik thinks are the best opportunities in the market right now.\n\nDon't Go Mainstream With Your Semiconductor Holdings\n\nMalik and a number of other market experts have touted the idea that there's a very broad and impressive rising tide raising all boats in the semi space. Accordingly, companies like Nvidia, AMD, and really the entire competitive set look investable here. Much of that has to do with low inventory and surging data center, AI, and general-purpose server demand.\n\nWhat's interesting is that Malik highlighted NXP Semiconductors (NXPI) as one of his top ideas. Malik specifically noted that NXP is one of his most attractive ideas in this space, with a key focus on the company's valuation.\n\nwww.barchart.com\n\nLooking at NXP's statistics above, I do think Malik and the other Citi analysts covering this name are onto something. With a forward price-earnings ratio under 20 times, that's a valuation that most investors can get behind. Despite being powered by extremely robust underlying structural growth trends (the AI revolution), NXPI stock is one that's trading at a discount to the broader market. That's tricky to find in this space and is encouraging on many fronts.\n\nNow, there is some rationale to this low multiple on a relative basis. NXP currently has a profit margin under 20%, which stands in stark contrast to a number of other chipmakers with margins in the 50% range or higher. That said, if pricing power improves broadly across the board (which Malik and others appear to indicate is possible or even likely), then this company's valuation is even more attractive.\n\nStory Continues\nTerms and Privacy Policy\nPrivacy Dashboard",
    "date": null,
    "summaries": {
      "gemma4:e4b": "No direct information about AMD found."
    },
    "sentiment_scores": {
      "gemma4:e4b": 0.4864
